A Client-Aware Multi-Agent System for Long-Horizon Portfolio Construction

How I built an explainable, constraint-driven investment workflow that blends valuation, momentum, macro, risk, and sentiment into disciplined position sizing.

Multi-agent scoring Constraint-first portfolio rules Explainable allocation QA & calibration loop
Arjan Singh, Team Leader
Student Investment Team
Jan. 26
2026

Investing gets much harder the moment you add real-world constraints: a long horizon, the need for steady compounding, limits on concentration, and a requirement that every decision be explainable. This post distills a complete end-to-end process for building a portfolio under those constraints, using a modular “multi-agent” scoring system and a portfolio-level rule layer that enforces risk control before trades are made.

The problem I wanted to solve

I wanted to build something that could consistently evaluate investment ideas without getting emotional or lazy. The challenge wasn't just finding good stocks—it was creating a system that would stop me from: (1) putting too much weight on any single idea, (2) chasing yesterday's winners, and (3) breaking my own rules when things got uncomfortable. Basically, I needed a framework that would keep me disciplined even when I didn't want to be.

The system in one sentence

Every stock is evaluated by five specialized agents—Value, Growth/Momentum, Macro-Regime Fit, Risk, and Sentiment—then blended into a single confidence score, and finally filtered by a portfolio “gating” layer that checks concentration, sector exposure, correlation overlap, and volatility contribution.

Why I automated the boring parts

After manually evaluating stocks for a few weeks, I noticed something frustrating: I kept asking the same questions over and over. "What's the P/E ratio?" "How's it been performing lately?" "Is this too correlated with what I already own?" It was tedious and error-prone. So instead of treating my brain like a spreadsheet, I built a system to handle the repetitive stuff. This freed me up to focus on the interesting questions—like why the agents disagreed on a particular stock, or whether the macro picture was shifting.

What I learned from testing it

Three positions became “teaching trades” because they forced clarity about how valuation, catalysts, and risk controls interact:

  • The momentum confirmation: One position taught me that when value and momentum align, but sentiment is mixed, you need to dig deeper. The quantitative signals are useful, but they're not the whole story.
  • The high-variance test: I held a volatile name that made me nervous every day. It forced me to trust the system's overall blend of signals instead of obsessing over daily moves. Good lesson in discipline.
  • Taiwan Semiconductor (TSM): a core holding example of valuation discount plus catalyst alignment, and a template for “anchor” positions.

Strategic rationale: what each holding was “for”

The portfolio was constructed as a blend of anchors and optionality: semiconductors provided structural exposure to computing infrastructure demand, software added recurring-revenue stability, healthcare dampened volatility through steadier earnings, and two smaller positions were reserved for upside with capped risk.

How conviction was generated (and constrained)

Diagrams from the report. The PDF included several visuals explaining how data moves through the pipeline and where constraints get enforced. They’re embedded below so the post reads like the report — but in a web-native format.

The engine’s key design choice was separating scoring from admission. First, candidates are scored quickly and consistently in parallel. Then, a portfolio rules layer rejects candidates that break concentration, sector, correlation, or risk limits. In other words: the system expresses conviction through position sizing, not emotion.

Why show the scores? Multi-agent systems can feel like a black box. A compact score table + heatmap makes it obvious which stocks are being carried by fundamentals, momentum, macro fit, risk controls, and sentiment — and where the system is conflicted.

Model safety: a QA loop with measurable triggers

A scoring model is only useful if it improves over time without becoming reactive. The report describes a structured learning loop: each analysis is logged with inputs and scores, and when a holding moves more than ±20% from its evaluation price, the system triggers a post-analysis audit to diagnose whether earnings, news/sentiment, sector rotation, or macro regime was the dominant driver. Adjustments are capped, versioned, backed up, and auditable.

The biggest improvement was not changing the goal—it was tightening the rules. Early weeks focused on building the agent framework; later weeks focused on stricter risk checks, data validation, and reducing unnecessary trading once the portfolio structure was set.

Takeaways you can reuse

  1. Standardize evaluation before you optimize picks. Consistency beats brilliance when you need explainability.
  2. Separate scoring from admission. Portfolio rules should be enforced before trades—not after drawdowns.
  3. Use sizing as your language of conviction. High-confidence ideas earn room; high-uncertainty ideas earn caps.
  4. Build a learning loop with triggers. A clear threshold (like ±20%) turns “post-mortems” into repeatable calibration.
